{"id":6521,"date":"2015-10-16T11:59:05","date_gmt":"2015-10-16T17:59:05","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/?p=6521"},"modified":"2018-12-07T16:08:31","modified_gmt":"2018-12-07T23:08:31","slug":"caring-for-succulents-in-winter","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/caring-for-succulents-in-winter\/","title":{"rendered":"Caring for Succulents in Winter"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><div class=\"fusion-fullwidth fullwidth-box fusion-builder-row-1 nonhundred-percent-fullwidth non-hundred-percent-height-scrolling\" style=\"background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0);background-position: center center;background-repeat: no-repeat;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;margin-bottom: 0px;margin-top: 0px;border-width: 0px 0px 0px 0px;border-color:#eae9e9;border-style:solid;\" ><div class=\"fusion-builder-row fusion-row\"><div class=\"fusion-layout-column fusion_builder_column fusion-builder-column-0 fusion_builder_column_1_1 1_1 fusion-one-full fusion-column-first fusion-column-last\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px;\"><div class=\"fusion-column-wrapper fusion-flex-column-wrapper-legacy\" style=\"background-position:left top;background-repeat:no-repeat;-webkit-background-size:cover;-moz-background-size:cover;-o-background-size:cover;background-size:cover;padding: 0px 0px 0px 0px;\"><div class=\"fusion-text fusion-text-1\"><p>Caring for succulents in winter doesn't have to keep you guessing! In this post you'll learn how to properly care for your succulents indoors over the winter, along with some tips for your outdoor succulent garden.<\/p>\n<p>Based on where you live and the <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/types-of-succulents-plants\/\">types of succulents<\/a> you are growing, your succulents may not be able to stay outside year round.<\/p>\n<p>If you do have tender succulents (those that can't handle freezing climates) and live in a climate with snow or many nights of freezing temperatures, you'll need to bring your succulents inside in order for them to survive.<\/p>\n<div id=\"attachment_6525\" style=\"width: 745px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-6525\" class=\"wp-image-6525 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Learn-how-to-properly-water-and-care-for-your-succulents-indoors-in-the-winter.jpg\" alt=\"Learn how to properly water and care for your succulents indoors in the winter\" width=\"735\" height=\"1099\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Learn-how-to-properly-water-and-care-for-your-succulents-indoors-in-the-winter-500x748.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Learn-how-to-properly-water-and-care-for-your-succulents-indoors-in-the-winter-700x1047.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Learn-how-to-properly-water-and-care-for-your-succulents-indoors-in-the-winter.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><p id=\"caption-attachment-6525\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Aloe variety, <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/types-of-succulents\/cotyledon-tomentosa-bears-paw\/\">Cotyledon tomentosa<\/a>, <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/types-of-succulents\/crassula-perforata-string-of-buttons\/\">Crassula perforata<\/a>,\u00a0<a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/types-of-succulents\/sedum-nussbaumerianum-coppertone-sedum\/\">Sedum nussbaumerianum<\/a>, Echeveria &#8216;Blue Rose' | <a href=\"http:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/where-to-buy-succulents\/\">Purchase Options<\/a><\/p><\/div>\n<h3>When should I bring my succulents inside for winter?<\/h3>\n<p>This is largely determined, again, by where you live and what you're growing. As a general rule, you'll want to bring your succulents in before the first frost. For many people in the US this is at the end of September.<\/p>\n<p>Of course, if you are growing <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/sempervivum-hens-and-chicks-color-changing-cold-hardy-succulents\/\">cold hardy succulents<\/a>, they can stay outside all winter.<\/p>\n<div id=\"attachment_12440\" style=\"width: 745px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-12440\" class=\"wp-image-12440 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/11\/Purple-Sempervivum-Hens-and-Chicks-2.jpg\" alt=\"Purple Sempervivum Hens and Chicks\" width=\"735\" height=\"919\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/11\/Purple-Sempervivum-Hens-and-Chicks-2-64x80.jpg 64w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/11\/Purple-Sempervivum-Hens-and-Chicks-2-200x250.jpg 200w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/11\/Purple-Sempervivum-Hens-and-Chicks-2-250x313.jpg 250w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/11\/Purple-Sempervivum-Hens-and-Chicks-2-400x500.jpg 400w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/11\/Purple-Sempervivum-Hens-and-Chicks-2-500x625.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/11\/Purple-Sempervivum-Hens-and-Chicks-2-585x731.jpg 585w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/11\/Purple-Sempervivum-Hens-and-Chicks-2-600x750.jpg 600w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/11\/Purple-Sempervivum-Hens-and-Chicks-2-700x875.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/11\/Purple-Sempervivum-Hens-and-Chicks-2.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><p id=\"caption-attachment-12440\" class=\"wp-caption-text\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/sempervivum-hens-and-chicks-cold-hardy-succulents\/\">Sempervivum variety<\/a><\/p><\/div>\n<p>It's important to know what <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/faq-items\/what-zone-do-i-live-in\/\">growing zone you live in.<\/a> At the least you should know the average low temperature for your area. For example: when I lived in Utah we were a Zone 5. Most of the succulents I owned at the time were for\u00a0Zone 9.<\/p>\n<p>All succulents rated higher than Zone 5 can't survive the cold, and need to be indoors for the winter.<\/p>\n<p>Since I currently live in the Phoenix area, a Zone 9, most of my succulents are fine outdoors year round. There are only a few succulents rated to a Zone 10 or 11 that will need to spend the winter inside.<\/p>\n<div id=\"attachment_8192\" style=\"width: 745px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-8192\" class=\"wp-image-8192 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/01\/This-Graptoveria-Fred-Ives-and-Aloe-have-amazing-colors.jpg\" alt=\"This Graptoveria Fred Ives and Aloe have amazing colors!\" width=\"735\" height=\"1103\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/01\/This-Graptoveria-Fred-Ives-and-Aloe-have-amazing-colors-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/01\/This-Graptoveria-Fred-Ives-and-Aloe-have-amazing-colors-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/01\/This-Graptoveria-Fred-Ives-and-Aloe-have-amazing-colors.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><p id=\"caption-attachment-8192\" class=\"wp-caption-text\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/types-of-succulents\/graptoveria-fred-ives\/\">Graptoveria &#8216;Fred Ives'<\/a>, Aloe variety<\/p><\/div>\n<p>So, start by <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/3-ways-to-identify-your-succulents\">identifying your succulents<\/a>. Then <a href=\"https:\/\/garden.org\/nga\/zipzone\/\" target=\"_blank\">determine what growing zone<\/a> you are in. See how the two compare! Bring in any plants that are rated higher than where you live.<\/p>\n<p>This video will also help you determine if your succulents need to be brought indoors for the winter:<\/p>\n<p><iframe src=\"https:\/\/www.youtube.com\/embed\/PSKVA8LDidM?rel=0&showinfo=0\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"><\/iframe><\/p>\n<h3>Moving Outdoor Succulents Inside<\/h3>\n<p>While you may be growing succulents inside all year round, succulents will benefit from being outside for at least part of the summer. Here's a check list to make sure the move from outside to inside goes as smoothly as possible:<\/p>\n<h5>Water Outside<\/h5>\n<p>Since it can be a hassle to <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/how-to-water-succulent-plants\/\">water<\/a>\u00a0succulents indoors (bringing them all to the sink, waiting for them to stop dripping, etc.) water them one last time outside.<\/p>\n<p>Try watering them 2-3 days before bringing them inside. This allows them to soak up the water they need and start to dry out. Then your shelf or table stays nice and dry once the succulents are inside.<\/p>\n<h5>Well Draining Soil<\/h5>\n<p>You'll also want to make sure (if they aren't already) that your succulents are in a <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/well-draining-soil-for-succulent-container-gardens\/\" rel=\"noopener\">well draining soil<\/a> in a <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/choosing-the-right-pot-for-your-succulents\/\" rel=\"noopener\">pot with a drainage hole<\/a>. Succulents grown indoors will do much better if they have the right soil and container.<\/p>\n<p>If you don't want to mix your own succulent soil, I've been using this <a href=\"https:\/\/www.bonsaijack.com\/Succulent_Soil_sas.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow sponsored\">succulent soil mix<\/a> from Bonsai Jack and love it! It's the same recipe I used to make myself, but now I don't have to slave away for hours making it. Your succulents will definitely thank you for putting them in the right soil.<\/p>\n<h5>Prep the Pot for Inside<\/h5>\n<p>When you are finally ready to bring your succulents inside, you'll want to make sure the pot is ready.\u00a0It's a good idea to wipe off the outside of the pot to remove any dirt, leaves or cobwebs that have become attached to the pot.<\/p>\n<p>Also be sure to remove any debris, such as dead leaves, from around or between your succulents. Dead organic material can easily cause your succulents to rot or become infected.<\/p>\n<p>I love my <a href=\"https:\/\/amzn.to\/2hL7kzC\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow sponsored\">mini tool kit<\/a> to help with this process! Once you've removed anything that doesn't belong, you can also add in or replace the top dressing to help the arrangement look extra cleaned up.<\/p>\n<div id=\"attachment_14461\" style=\"width: 838px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-14461\" class=\"wp-image-14461 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Cleaning-up-your-pots-of-succulents-before-moving-inside-for-the-winter-makes-a-huge-difference.jpg\" alt=\"Cleaning up your pots of succulents before moving inside for the winter makes a huge difference!\" width=\"828\" height=\"1103\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Cleaning-up-your-pots-of-succulents-before-moving-inside-for-the-winter-makes-a-huge-difference-60x80.jpg 60w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Cleaning-up-your-pots-of-succulents-before-moving-inside-for-the-winter-makes-a-huge-difference-200x266.jpg 200w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Cleaning-up-your-pots-of-succulents-before-moving-inside-for-the-winter-makes-a-huge-difference-250x333.jpg 250w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Cleaning-up-your-pots-of-succulents-before-moving-inside-for-the-winter-makes-a-huge-difference-400x533.jpg 400w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Cleaning-up-your-pots-of-succulents-before-moving-inside-for-the-winter-makes-a-huge-difference-500x666.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Cleaning-up-your-pots-of-succulents-before-moving-inside-for-the-winter-makes-a-huge-difference-585x779.jpg 585w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Cleaning-up-your-pots-of-succulents-before-moving-inside-for-the-winter-makes-a-huge-difference-600x799.jpg 600w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Cleaning-up-your-pots-of-succulents-before-moving-inside-for-the-winter-makes-a-huge-difference-700x932.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Cleaning-up-your-pots-of-succulents-before-moving-inside-for-the-winter-makes-a-huge-difference-768x1023.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Cleaning-up-your-pots-of-succulents-before-moving-inside-for-the-winter-makes-a-huge-difference-800x1066.jpg 800w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Cleaning-up-your-pots-of-succulents-before-moving-inside-for-the-winter-makes-a-huge-difference.jpg 828w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 828px) 100vw, 828px\" \/><p id=\"caption-attachment-14461\" class=\"wp-caption-text\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/types-of-succulents\/crassula-ovata-gollum\/?aff=2\">Crassula ovata &#8216;Gollum'<\/a><\/p><\/div>\n<h5>Check for Bugs<\/h5>\n<p>You don't want any visitors when you move your succulents inside. Inspect your succulents closely for signs of <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/kill-mealybugs-on-succulents\/\">mealybugs<\/a>, the most common succulent pest.<\/p>\n<p>Also look for any other little bugs around your plants. I know at my house ants and potato bugs love to hang out in my pots. I see spiders frequently as well.<\/p>\n<p>Try to remove these little guys as much as possible to keep your succulents healthier indoors.<\/p>\n<h5>Refresh the arrangement<\/h5>\n<p>As your succulent grows it's going to start shedding leaves. It's always a good idea to keep your succulents well <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/pruning-maintaining-succulent-arrangement\/\">pruned and maintained<\/a>. This is especially important before bringing succulents in for the winter.<\/p>\n<p>Use your fingers or the tweezers from the <a href=\"https:\/\/amzn.to\/2hL7kzC\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow sponsored\">mini garden tool kit<\/a> to remove as many of the dead leaves as possible. This will help prevent your succulent from rotting indoors.<\/p>\n<div id=\"attachment_23362\" style=\"width: 3658px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-23362\" class=\"wp-image-23362 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Remove-dead-leaves-from-succulents-before-bringing-them-inside-for-the-winter-1.jpg\" alt=\"Remove dead leaves from succulents before bringing them inside for the winter\" width=\"3648\" height=\"5472\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Remove-dead-leaves-from-succulents-before-bringing-them-inside-for-the-winter-1-53x80.jpg 53w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Remove-dead-leaves-from-succulents-before-bringing-them-inside-for-the-winter-1-200x300.jpg 200w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Remove-dead-leaves-from-succulents-before-bringing-them-inside-for-the-winter-1-250x375.jpg 250w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Remove-dead-leaves-from-succulents-before-bringing-them-inside-for-the-winter-1-400x600.jpg 400w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Remove-dead-leaves-from-succulents-before-bringing-them-inside-for-the-winter-1-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Remove-dead-leaves-from-succulents-before-bringing-them-inside-for-the-winter-1-585x878.jpg 585w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Remove-dead-leaves-from-succulents-before-bringing-them-inside-for-the-winter-1-600x900.jpg 600w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Remove-dead-leaves-from-succulents-before-bringing-them-inside-for-the-winter-1-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Remove-dead-leaves-from-succulents-before-bringing-them-inside-for-the-winter-1-768x1152.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Remove-dead-leaves-from-succulents-before-bringing-them-inside-for-the-winter-1-800x1200.jpg 800w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Remove-dead-leaves-from-succulents-before-bringing-them-inside-for-the-winter-1-1200x1800.jpg 1200w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Remove-dead-leaves-from-succulents-before-bringing-them-inside-for-the-winter-1.jpg 3648w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 3648px) 100vw, 3648px\" \/><p id=\"caption-attachment-23362\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Crested <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/types-of-succulents\/echeveria-runyonii-topsy-turvy\/?aff=2\">Echeveria &#8216;Topsy Turvy'<\/a><\/p><\/div>\n<p>If any of your succulents have died over the summer, now is a great time to fill in the holes. The arrangement below stayed looking great over the summer, except for one <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/what-are-monocarpic-succulents\/\" rel=\"noopener\">monocarpic succulent.<\/a> After it bloomed, it left a big hole.<\/p>\n<p>I filled in the hole with a few <a href=\"https:\/\/thesucculentsource.com\/collections\/succulent-cuttings?aff=20\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow sponsored\">succulent cuttings<\/a> and it looks complete again! I also added some <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/top-dressing-decorative-rocks\/\">top dressing<\/a> since it didn't have any.<\/p>\n<div id=\"attachment_14462\" style=\"width: 948px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-14462\" class=\"wp-image-14462 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Keep-your-succulents-looking-great-all-year-with-the-tips-in-this-post.jpg\" alt=\"Keep your succulents looking great all year with the tips in this post\" width=\"938\" height=\"1103\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Keep-your-succulents-looking-great-all-year-with-the-tips-in-this-post-68x80.jpg 68w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Keep-your-succulents-looking-great-all-year-with-the-tips-in-this-post-200x235.jpg 200w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Keep-your-succulents-looking-great-all-year-with-the-tips-in-this-post-250x294.jpg 250w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Keep-your-succulents-looking-great-all-year-with-the-tips-in-this-post-400x470.jpg 400w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Keep-your-succulents-looking-great-all-year-with-the-tips-in-this-post-500x588.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Keep-your-succulents-looking-great-all-year-with-the-tips-in-this-post-585x688.jpg 585w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Keep-your-succulents-looking-great-all-year-with-the-tips-in-this-post-600x706.jpg 600w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Keep-your-succulents-looking-great-all-year-with-the-tips-in-this-post-700x823.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Keep-your-succulents-looking-great-all-year-with-the-tips-in-this-post-768x903.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Keep-your-succulents-looking-great-all-year-with-the-tips-in-this-post-800x941.jpg 800w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Keep-your-succulents-looking-great-all-year-with-the-tips-in-this-post.jpg 938w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 938px) 100vw, 938px\" \/><p id=\"caption-attachment-14462\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Aloe variety, <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/types-of-succulents\/cotyledon-tomentosa-bears-paw\/\">Cotyledon tomentosa<\/a>,\u00a0<a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/types-of-succulents\/crassula-perforata-string-of-buttons\/\">Crassula perforata<\/a>, <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/where-to-buy-succulents\/\">Sempervivum &#8216;Green Wheel'<\/a>, <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/types-of-succulents\/sedum-nussbaumerianum-coppertone-sedum\/\">Sedum nussbaumerianum<\/a>, Echeveria &#8216;Blue Rose'. Graptosedum &#8216;Alpenglow' | <a href=\"http:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/where-to-buy-succulents\/\">Purchase Options<\/a><\/p><\/div>\n<h3>Winter Watering for Succulents<\/h3>\n<p>Now that your succulents are inside, it's time to start taking care of them!<\/p>\n<p>Many succulents are dormant in the winter so they won't need as much water. However, some are actively growing and will need more attention.<\/p>\n<p>I have an entire post on <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/succulent-dormancy-table\/\">dormancy<\/a> that includes a list of which succulents are winter growers and which are summer growers. <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/succulent-dormancy-table\/\">Click here<\/a> to read it and determine if your succulents are actively growing or dormant in winter.<\/p>\n<p>You can also check out this post if you need help <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/3-ways-to-identify-your-succulents\/\" rel=\"noopener\">identifying your succulents<\/a>.<\/p>\n<p>If your succulents are winter growers they will likely need more frequent watering. My <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/types-of-succulents\/aeonium-arboreum-zwartkop\/\" rel=\"noopener\">Aeonium &#8216;Zwartkop'<\/a>\u00a0(a winter grower) always seems to be a water hog over the winter.<\/p>\n<div id=\"attachment_7807\" style=\"width: 745px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-7807\" class=\"wp-image-7807 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2116\/08\/Aeonium-Zwartkop-and-Portulacaria-afra-variegata.jpg\" alt=\"Aeonium Zwartkop and Portulacaria afra variegata\" width=\"735\" height=\"1102\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2116\/08\/Aeonium-Zwartkop-and-Portulacaria-afra-variegata-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2116\/08\/Aeonium-Zwartkop-and-Portulacaria-afra-variegata-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2116\/08\/Aeonium-Zwartkop-and-Portulacaria-afra-variegata.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><p id=\"caption-attachment-7807\" class=\"wp-caption-text\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/types-of-succulents\/aeonium-arboreum-zwartkop\/\">Aeonium &#8216;Zwartkop'<\/a>, <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/types-of-succulents\/portulacaria-afra-elephant-bush\/\">Portulacaria afra variegata<\/a><\/p><\/div>\n<p>As a general rule though, you'll only want to <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/how-to-water-succulent-plants\/\">water your plants<\/a> when the soil is completely dry. Let them go several days, even a week or two between watering.<\/p>\n<p>Your succulent will tell you when it needs water. If you're not sure what that looks like, be sure to <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/signs-succulents-need-water\/\">click here<\/a> and grab our free cheat sheet, <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/signs-succulents-need-water\/\">Signs Your Succulents Need Water<\/a>.<\/p>\n<p>The airflow indoors is more limited than outside so without the <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/well-draining-soil-for-succulent-container-gardens\/\" rel=\"noopener\">proper soil<\/a> it's very likely your succulents will stay wet for too long. Watering too frequently is the quickest way to kill your succulent.<\/p>\n<p>Keep in mind that succulents near a heating vent might need more frequent watering. The direct air and warmer temperatures can dry things out more quickly.<\/p>\n<div id=\"attachment_6526\" style=\"width: 1010px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-6526\" class=\"wp-image-6526 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Learn-how-to-properly-water-succulents-in-the-winter.jpg\" alt=\"Learn how to properly water succulents in the winter\" width=\"1000\" height=\"667\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Learn-how-to-properly-water-succulents-in-the-winter-500x334.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Learn-how-to-properly-water-succulents-in-the-winter-700x467.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Learn-how-to-properly-water-succulents-in-the-winter.jpg 1000w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px\" \/><p id=\"caption-attachment-6526\" class=\"wp-caption-text\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/types-of-succulents\/crassula-arborescens-undulatifolia-ripple-jade\/\">Crassula arborescens undulatifolia<\/a>, Haworthia reinwardtii, <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/types-of-succulents\/sedum-clavatum\/\">Sedum clavatum<\/a>\u00a0 | <a href=\"http:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/where-to-buy-succulents\/\">Purchase Options<\/a><\/p><\/div>\n<h3>Plenty of Sunlight<\/h3>\n<p>One of the most difficult things about growing succulents indoors, especially over the winter, is making sure they get enough sunlight.<\/p>\n<p>You'll want to place your succulents near the brightest window in your home. The ideal window will get bright, indirect sunlight all day.<\/p>\n<p>Since the winter days are shorter this is especially important. Succulents need at least 8 hours of bright indirect sunlight each day to maintain their shape indoors.<\/p>\n<p>With lots of gray or cloudy days in the winter you may find your succulents begin to <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/stretched-out-succulents\/\">stretch<\/a> out or lean toward the window. This is a sign they aren't getting enough light.<\/p>\n<p>In this case, you can rotate your succulents to help offset any leaning. But in order to prevent stretching you will need to supplement with a\u00a0<a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/choosing-the-right-grow-light-do-you-need-a-grow-light\/\" rel=\"noopener\">grow light<\/a>.<\/p>\n<p>Make sure you don't run the lights 24\/7 as succulents do need dark at night to complete their regular growth cycle.<\/p>\n<div id=\"attachment_6531\" style=\"width: 1010px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-6531\" class=\"wp-image-6531 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Succulents-will-lean-toward-the-light-if-they-arent-getting-enough.jpg\" alt=\"Succulents will lean toward the light if they aren't getting enough\" width=\"1000\" height=\"667\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Succulents-will-lean-toward-the-light-if-they-arent-getting-enough-500x334.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Succulents-will-lean-toward-the-light-if-they-arent-getting-enough-700x467.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Succulents-will-lean-toward-the-light-if-they-arent-getting-enough.jpg 1000w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px\" \/><p id=\"caption-attachment-6531\" class=\"wp-caption-text\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/types-of-succulents\/crassula-ovata-gollum\/?aff=2\">Crassula ovata &#8216;Gollum'<\/a><\/p><\/div>\n<p>For succulents that do get stretched out or grow tall and leggy, at the end of the winter you can cut off the tops and <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/propagating-succulents\/\" rel=\"noopener\">propagate them<\/a>! Then you'll have even more plants for the summer!<\/p>\n<p>Since most succulents aren't growing as quickly over the winter, this is best done in the spring. For more details on how to do this, you can check out my post on <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/stretched-out-succulents\/\">stretching succulents here<\/a>.<\/p>\n<\/div><div class=\"fusion-clearfix\"><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/div><div class=\"fusion-fullwidth fullwidth-box fusion-builder-row-2 nonhundred-percent-fullwidth non-hundred-percent-height-scrolling\" style=\"background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0);background-position: center center;background-repeat: no-repeat;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;margin-bottom: 0px;margin-top: 0px;border-width: 0px 0px 0px 0px;border-color:#eae9e9;border-style:solid;\" ><div class=\"fusion-builder-row fusion-row\"><div class=\"fusion-layout-column fusion_builder_column fusion-builder-column-1 fusion_builder_column_1_1 1_1 fusion-one-full fusion-column-first fusion-column-last\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px;\"><div class=\"fusion-column-wrapper fusion-flex-column-wrapper-legacy\" style=\"background-position:left top;background-repeat:no-repeat;-webkit-background-size:cover;-moz-background-size:cover;-o-background-size:cover;background-size:cover;padding: 0px 0px 0px 0px;\"><div class=\"fusion-text fusion-text-2\"><h3>Frost Damage on Tender Succulents<\/h3>\n<p>If succulents are left out in temperatures below what they can tolerate, you'll begin to see damage from the frost or cold. It's not a pretty sight!<\/p>\n<p>Don't risk leaving your succulents out during extreme cold, even if they appear to be ok. Often the frost damage takes 2-3 days to show up.<\/p>\n<p>This happened to me while living in Utah. I left my tender succulents outside for 3-4 nights when temperatures got below freezing.<\/p>\n<p>They looked fine on the first two days, but the third day&#8230;<\/p>\n<div id=\"attachment_23352\" style=\"width: 4079px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-23352\" class=\"wp-image-23352 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-on-Non-Cold-Hardy-Succulents.jpg\" alt=\"Frost Damage on Non-Cold Hardy Succulents\" width=\"4069\" height=\"2713\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-on-Non-Cold-Hardy-Succulents-80x53.jpg 80w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-on-Non-Cold-Hardy-Succulents-200x133.jpg 200w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-on-Non-Cold-Hardy-Succulents-250x167.jpg 250w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-on-Non-Cold-Hardy-Succulents-400x267.jpg 400w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-on-Non-Cold-Hardy-Succulents-500x333.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-on-Non-Cold-Hardy-Succulents-585x390.jpg 585w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-on-Non-Cold-Hardy-Succulents-600x400.jpg 600w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-on-Non-Cold-Hardy-Succulents-700x467.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-on-Non-Cold-Hardy-Succulents-768x512.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-on-Non-Cold-Hardy-Succulents-800x533.jpg 800w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-on-Non-Cold-Hardy-Succulents-1200x800.jpg 1200w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-on-Non-Cold-Hardy-Succulents.jpg 4069w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 4069px) 100vw, 4069px\" \/><p id=\"caption-attachment-23352\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Graptoveria variety<\/p><\/div>\n<p>The most common thing I saw on these plants was dark mushy tissue. Weather that is too cold can cause the plant cells to burst, having the appearance of rot.<\/p>\n<div id=\"attachment_23353\" style=\"width: 4079px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-23353\" class=\"wp-image-23353 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-occurs-if-you-shock-your-indoor-succulents-with-extreme-cold-weather.jpg\" alt=\"Frost Damage occurs if you shock your indoor succulents with extreme cold weather\" width=\"4069\" height=\"2713\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-occurs-if-you-shock-your-indoor-succulents-with-extreme-cold-weather-80x53.jpg 80w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-occurs-if-you-shock-your-indoor-succulents-with-extreme-cold-weather-200x133.jpg 200w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-occurs-if-you-shock-your-indoor-succulents-with-extreme-cold-weather-250x167.jpg 250w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-occurs-if-you-shock-your-indoor-succulents-with-extreme-cold-weather-400x267.jpg 400w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-occurs-if-you-shock-your-indoor-succulents-with-extreme-cold-weather-500x333.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-occurs-if-you-shock-your-indoor-succulents-with-extreme-cold-weather-585x390.jpg 585w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-occurs-if-you-shock-your-indoor-succulents-with-extreme-cold-weather-600x400.jpg 600w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-occurs-if-you-shock-your-indoor-succulents-with-extreme-cold-weather-700x467.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-occurs-if-you-shock-your-indoor-succulents-with-extreme-cold-weather-768x512.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-occurs-if-you-shock-your-indoor-succulents-with-extreme-cold-weather-800x533.jpg 800w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-occurs-if-you-shock-your-indoor-succulents-with-extreme-cold-weather-1200x800.jpg 1200w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/10\/Frost-Damage-occurs-if-you-shock-your-indoor-succulents-with-extreme-cold-weather.jpg 4069w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 4069px) 100vw, 4069px\" \/><p id=\"caption-attachment-23353\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Aeonium variety<\/p><\/div>\n<p>Aeoniums (above and below) are generally very sensitive to freezing temperatures. The one below was protected by some other plants so it didn't suffer as much damage.<\/p>\n<p><div id=\"attachment_23355\"